{{Infobox person |name = Mike Strautmanis |image = Michael Strautmanis portrait.jpg |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|3|24}} |birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S. |death_date = |death_place = |party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] |alma_mater = [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]] }} '''Michael Strautmanis''' (born March 24, 1969)<ref name=BOpeeps>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/html/magazine/2009-inauguration-gallery/index.html?WT.mc_id=PO-D-I-NYT-MOD-MOD-MII-ROS-0109-NA&WT.mc_ev=click|title=Obama's People|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> is an American lawyer. [[President-Elect]] [[Barack Obama]] announced on December 5, 2008, that Strautmanis would serve as Chief of Staff to [[Valerie Jarrett]] who is to be the Assistant to the President for Intergovernmental Relations and Public Engagement.<ref>[http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/president_elect_obama_announces_more_key_white_house_staff/ President-elect Obama announces more key White House staff] ''Office of the President-elect and Office of the Vice President-elect'', December 5, 2008</ref> He served as Chief Counsel and the Director of Public Liaison and Intergovernmental Affairs on Obama's [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama|presidential transition team]].<ref name="usnews">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/articles/news/campaign-2008/2008/11/05/obama-names-transition-team.html |title=Obama Names Transition Team |accessdate=2008-11-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208205543/http://www.usnews.com/articles/news/campaign-2008/2008/11/05/obama-names-transition-team.html |archivedate=2008-12-08 |df= }}</ref><ref name="uiuc">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.uiuc.edu/content/newsletter/2008/march.asp |title=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign - Dean's Newsletter |accessdate=2008-11-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720141726/http://www.law.uiuc.edu/content/newsletter/2008/march.asp |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>
In March, 2013, he announced his resignation from the White House staff in order to accept a post with the [[Walt Disney Corporation]] specializing in corporate citizenship.<ref>[http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2013/03/strautmanis_leaving_white_hous.html Strautmanis leaving White House (Chicago Sun-Times article-March 13, 2013)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704152159/http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2013/03/strautmanis_leaving_white_hous.html |date=July 4, 2014 }}</ref> In January, 2016, he became the Vice President of Civic Engagement for the [[Obama Foundation]].<ref>https://www.obama.org/whats-next/leadership/</ref>
In 2018, Strautmanis detailed his longstanding relationship with Michelle and Barack Obama and his experiences in the Obama White House in a chapter in ''[https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/9780143133292/ West Wingers: Stories from the Dream Chasers, Change Makers, and Hope Creators Inside the Obama White House]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/572629/west-wingers-by-edited-by-gautam-raghavan/|title=West Wingers {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|language=en-US}}</ref>
Previously Strautmanis served the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] as Chief of Staff to the [[general counsel]] at the [[United States Agency for International Development]], and then-U.S. Congressman [[Rod Blagojevich]] as legislative director.<ref name=BOpeeps/> He worked for the [[American Association for Justice]].<ref name="uiuc"/>
A [[Chicago, Illinois]] native,<ref name="uiuc"/> Strautmanis was educated at the law school of the [[University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign]]. He started his legal career as a [[paralegal]] at the Sidley, Austin law firm, where he met the Obamas.<ref name="gwu">{{cite web| url=http://www.gwu.edu/~action/2008/obama/obama070708pr.html | title=Obama Campaign Announces Congressional Liaison Team | accessdate=2008-11-07 }}</ref>
